So, we're just going to have
an informal chat to talk

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:29.700
about their experience with the
Stradivari instruments and also

00:01:29.700 --> 00:01:34.460
with the repertoire and then also
bringing Kati's piece to life

00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:36.790
as they've given the
world premiere already

00:01:36.790 --> 00:01:39.920
and some other performances of it.

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:42.060
Just some context about
this evening.

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:44.770
This is our annual
Stradivari concert,

00:01:44.770 --> 00:01:47.270
also known as the Stradivari
Anniversary Concert.

00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:50.380
And we invite a string quartet and
sometimes some other guest artists

00:01:50.380 --> 00:01:54.370 position:56%
to perform on the library's historic
string instrument collection.

00:01:54.370 --> 00:01:58.750
Specifically, the violins, and
viola, and cello that were donated

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:02.650
by Gertrude Clarke
Whittall beginning in 1935.

00:02:02.650 --> 00:02:03.950
She actually built this room.

00:02:03.950 --> 00:02:06.130
We're in the Whittall
Pavilion here at the library.

00:02:06.130 --> 00:02:10.140
And she was a very wonderful
philanthropist who liked to compete

00:02:10.140 --> 00:02:14.400
with Mrs. Coolidge who of
course build the hall next door.

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:15.880
There's a difference
of about 10 years

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:18.810
between Mrs. Coolidge
giving her initial gift

00:02:18.810 --> 00:02:21.240
and then Mrs. Whittall's
gift of the instrument.

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:24.130
Tonight's events mark
the 80th Anniversary

00:02:24.130 --> 00:02:26.250
of the first Stradivari
Anniversary Concert.

00:02:26.250 --> 00:02:28.590
So, this is a lot of redundant
use of the word anniversary.

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:31.220
I'm sorry and we're very pleased

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:34.940
to be featuring the
Cecilia Quartet tonight.

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:39.150
