00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:45.960
&gt;&gt; NICHOLAS BROWN: The
title of your piece is

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:48.030
of course "Tantric Variations."

00:10:48.030 --> 00:10:50.740
Could you tell us a little
bit about the through process

00:10:50.740 --> 00:10:54.470
that went behind creating the piece
and then maybe also some thoughts

00:10:54.470 --> 00:10:56.890
of the use of variation form.

00:10:56.890 --> 00:10:59.450
&gt;&gt; KATI AGOCS: Yes, so Tantric
is from the Sanskrit Tan

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:02.230 position:56%
which means to weave out or to spin.

00:11:02.230 --> 00:11:06.010
So, we weaved this trans of our
nature into a unified whole.

00:11:06.010 --> 00:11:09.390
And I always have been fascinated
by variations, but I never,

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:12.390
this is my first time
working in variations.

00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:15.100
And the thing about
variations is it's usually,

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:17.390
composers usually do
discrete variations

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:19.400
because it's easier to do that.

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:24.100
It's harder to make a long form,
a continuous form with them

00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:27.750
because it's hard to have
enough textural contrast.

00:11:27.750 --> 00:11:29.720
But I'm really interested
in large form.

00:11:29.720 --> 00:11:33.700
I like my forms to be continuous,
not in separate movements.

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:36.590
So, what I ended up
doing was taking a very,

00:11:36.590 --> 00:11:38.380
very simple elemental motive.

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:44.070 position:56%
It's just like a little turn figure,
or embellishing of a single note,

00:11:44.070 --> 00:11:48.270
kind of like, daa,
da, da, da, da, dum.

00:11:48.270 --> 00:11:52.270
And I just use this motive
throughout the entire piece,

00:11:52.270 --> 00:11:56.320
the entire piece is in
medication just on this one motive.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:59.350
But what I do is the motive
gets increasingly melodic

00:11:59.350 --> 00:12:03.130
and it gets spun out as
the piece progresses.

00:12:03.130 --> 00:12:06.160
So, you hear it spun
into longer melodies

00:12:06.160 --> 00:12:09.010
and then the variations start
to interrupt each other,

00:12:09.010 --> 00:12:12.400
even invade each other so
the form becomes dynamic.

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:17.430
And ultimately it's kind of a
purification process of this motive

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:21.310
because it flowers into a sort
of fuller version of itself.

00:12:21.310 --> 00:12:23.020
And what you should listen
for is there's a duet

00:12:23.020 --> 00:12:26.360
between the two violins close
to the end where it sort

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.760
of reaches its full self.

00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:30.280
and then at the end
it gets distilled

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:33.700 position:56%
down to just a single note, because
we don't really need to turn anymore

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:36.130 position:56%
by that point, it's sort of
purified down, and so the piece ends

00:12:36.130 --> 00:12:38.870
with just single harmonics
on the violins.

00:12:38.870 --> 00:12:42.270 position:56%
So, it's kind of like a purification
process that we all go on together,

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:43.940
journey that we all go on.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:46.600
Me as the composer, and
you as the audience,

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:47.990
and the quartet, obviously.

00:12:47.990 --> 00:12:49.520
And I think if I had to sum it up,

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:52.630
it would be like developing
variations then,

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:55.330
sort of like what Brahms would
have done, but my own version

00:12:55.330 --> 00:12:57.380
of developing variations.

